<statement>
<p>Solve this system of equations using elimination.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{2}{x}-{7}{y}={10}</m> </p>
<p>
  <m>\displaystyle-{x}+{6}{y}=-{10}</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="8"/></p>

</statement>
<solution>
<p><ul><li><m>\displaystyle{\left(-{2},-{2}\right)}</m></li></ul></p><p>We chose (for no special reason) to use the first equation to eliminate x from the second equation.</p>
<p>To eliminate we need the scaled version of equation one to have a coefficient of --1. So we scale by <m>\displaystyle--\frac{{1}}{{2}}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-\frac{{-{1}}}{{2}}{\left({2}{x}+-{7}{y}\right)}=-\frac{{-{1}}}{{2}}{\left({10}\right)}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-{\left(-{1}\right)}{x}+-{3.5}{y}={5}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-{x}+{6}{y}=-{10}</m></p>
<p>Adding these two equations gives us</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{2.5}{y}=-{5}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{y}=-\frac{{5}}{{2.5}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{y}=-{2}</m></p>
<p>Finally we can substitute this y value into the first equation to solve for x.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{2}{x}+-{7}{\left(-{2}\right)}={10}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{2}{x}+{\left({14}\right)}={10}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{2}{x}={10}-{\left({14}\right)}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{2}{x}=-{4}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{x}=-\frac{{4}}{{2}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{x}=-{2}</m></p>
<p>Thus the answer is <m>\displaystyle{\left(-{2},-{2}\right)}</m>.</p>

</solution>
</myopenmath>